<div class="documentTop">
  
  <h1>Stoltenberg's 2nd Government</h1>
  
  <p>&nbsp;<img alt="Regjeringen samlet på Slottsplassen 20. oktober 2009. Foto: Scanpix" src="/upload/SMK/Portrettbilde/regjeringen/Regjeringen-på-Slottsplassen-20.10.09_540x270_fotoScanpix.jpg" />&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Jens Stoltenberg's second government was appointed by King Harald V on 17 October 2005. It is a majority government representing the Labour Party, the Socialist Left Party and the Centre Party. </strong></p>
<p>Picture taken&nbsp;20 October 2009.</p>
<p>From the left: Minister of Children, Equality and Social Inclusion Audun Lysbakken (Soc), Minister of Culture Anniken Huitfeldt (Lab), Minister and Chief of Staff at the Office of the Prime Minister Karl Eirik Schjøtt-Pedersen (Lab), Minister of Fisheries and Coastal Affairs Lisbeth Berg-Hansen (Lab), Minister of Justice and the Police Knut Storberget (Lab), Minister of Defence Grete&nbsp;Faremo (Lab), Minister of Petroleum and Energy Terje Riis-Johansen (Cent), Minister of Health and Care Services Anne-Grete Strøm-Erichsen (Lab), Minister of Local Government and Regional Development Liv Signe Navarsete (Cent), Minister of the Environment and International Development Erik Solheim (Soc), Prime Minister Jens Stoltenberg (Lab), Minister of Trade and Industry Trond Giske (Lab), Minister of Education Kristin Halvorsen (Soc), Minister of Research and Higher Education&nbsp;Tora Aasland (Soc), Minister of Foreign Affairs Jonas Gahr Støre (Lab), Minister of Labour Hanne Bjurstrøm (Lab), Minister of Finance Sigbjørn Johnsen (Lab), Minister of Government Administration, Reform and Church Affairs Rigmor Aasrud (Lab), Minister of Transport and Communications Magnhild Meltveit Kleppa (Cent) and Minister of Agriculture and Food Lars Peder Brekk (Cent). </p>
<p>Photo: Scanpix</p>
